definition.value: A member of the class of indenes that is 2,4,5,7a-tetrahydro-1H-indene substituted by methyl groups at positions 1, 4, 4 and 7a and by a hydroxy group at position 2.
A racemate comprising equimolar amounts of 2-methyl-D-serine and 2-methyl-L-serine.
A derivative of viomycin having a phospho group attached to the side-chain OH group of one of the serine residues.

A synthetic alpha-glucosyl-functionalized stereospecifically numbered glycerol phosphate (GroP) oligomer in which the alpha-glucosyl substituent is located at the terminal unit of an sn-3-GroP hexamer.
An oligomer comprised principally of glycerol phosphate units.
A synthetic stereospecifically numbered glycerol phosphate (GroP) oligomer. The structure of an sn-3-GroP hexamer, it can be conjugated to a protein through a 6-aminohexyl linker.
A synthetic stereospecifically numbered glycerol phosphate (GroP) oligomer. The structure of an sn-3-GroP pentamer, it can be conjugated to a protein through a 6-aminohexyl linker.
A hydrate that is the monohydrate of L-dehydroascorbic acid.

An aminoalcohol that is N(1)-(5-aminopentyl)pentane-1,5-diamine substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 2, 2', 4 and 4' (the 2R,4S,2'R,4'S-stereoisomer). It is a toxin produced by several plant species and the casual agent of gousiekte (''quick'' disease).

A member of the class of pterins that is 3,4,5,6,7,8-hexahydropteridine substituted by an amino group at position 2 and oxo groups at positions 4, 6 and 7. It is a pigment found in the wings of butterflies.
